A Turdus pilaris is a species of bird commonly known as the fieldfare. 
It has a distinctive plumage, with a grey head, rusty-brown wings and back, and a white underbelly. 
Its feathers are glossy and provide a sleek appearance. 
The fieldfare has striking black and white markings on its face and wings, giving it a unique appearance. 
It has a rounded body with a short, curved beak, and relatively long legs and tail. 
Fieldfares are typically found in open fields and woodlands, particularly in parts of Eurasia. 
They are migratory birds and can be seen gathering in large flocks during the winter months.
